<section id="philosophy">
    <h2>Functional Medicine Approach</h2>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Core Philosophy</h3>
        <blockquote>
            "Food is not just calories - it's information. Every bite you eat talks to your genes, hormones, immune system, and microbiome. Heart disease, diabetes, and obesity are not separate diseases - they're one disease: dysfunction caused by the Standard American Diet."
        </blockquote>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Principles</h3>

    <h4>1. Food is Medicine</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Food provides instructions to your body, not just fuel</li>
        <li>What you eat affects gene expression, hormone signaling, and inflammation</li>
        <li>Dietary change is often more powerful than medication</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>2. Everything is Connected</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Gut health affects brain health affects heart health</li>
        <li>You can't treat one system in isolation</li>
        <li>Root causes often affect multiple organs</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>3. Chronic Disease Has Common Roots</h4>
    <p>Dr. Hyman argues that most chronic diseases share common underlying causes:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Poor diet:</strong> Processed foods, sugar, inflammatory oils</li>
        <li><strong>Toxins:</strong> Environmental exposures</li>
        <li><strong>Allergens:</strong> Hidden food sensitivities</li>
        <li><strong>Microbiome disruption:</strong> Gut dysbiosis</li>
        <li><strong>Stress:</strong> Chronic activation of stress response</li>
        <li><strong>Nutrient deficiencies:</strong> Despite "adequate" calories</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>4. Personalized Medicine</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>No single diet works for everyone</li>
        <li>Testing reveals individual needs</li>
        <li>Treatment plans must be individualized</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>The "Diabesity" Concept</h3>
        <p>Dr. Hyman coined the term "diabesity" to describe the continuum from mild insulin resistance through metabolic syndrome to full diabetes - emphasizing that these aren't separate diseases but different stages of the same metabolic dysfunction.</p>
    </div>
</section>

